# Page folder structure

Routes map to folders under `src/pages/`. The page component file is always `index.tsx`.

## Mapping

| Route | File |
|-------|------|
| `/` | `src/pages/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet` | `src/pages/alphabet/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/hiragana` | `src/pages/alphabet/hiragana/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/katakana` | `src/pages/alphabet/katakana/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise/romaji` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/romaji/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise/character` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/character/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise/listen` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/listen/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise/script-pair` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/script-pair/index.tsx` |
| `/alphabet/exercise/writing` | `src/pages/alphabet/exercise/writing/index.tsx` |

## Course routes (exception: generic, not folder-per-route)

Course pages are shared and parameterized by `level: CourseLevel`, so they do NOT follow the folder-per-route `index.tsx` pattern. They live as flat files in `src/pages/course/` and are registered once in `src/app.tsx` by looping `COURSE_LEVELS` (`n5`–`n1`, `frontend`):

| Route | File |
|-------|------|
| `/:level` | `src/pages/course/course-page.tsx` |
| `/:level/lesson/:lessonId` | `src/pages/course/lesson-page.tsx` |
| `/:level/lesson/:lessonId/exercise` | `src/pages/course/exercise-page.tsx` |
| `/:level/lesson/:lessonId/listening` | `src/pages/course/listening-page.tsx` |
| `/:level/lesson/:lessonId/reading` | `src/pages/course/reading-page.tsx` |

## Colocation

- Put route-specific helpers next to the page (e.g. `exercise/exercise-quiz.ts`).
- Shared code for a route segment stays in that segment folder (e.g. `alphabet/alphabet-chart.tsx` for hiragana + katakana).
- Reusable UI stays in `src/components/`.

## New pages

When adding a route `/foo/bar`, create `src/pages/foo/bar/index.tsx` and register it in `src/constants/routes.ts` and `src/app.tsx`.

## Imports

Prefer `@/pages/...` path aliases. Use relative imports only for siblings in the same route folder.
